  "prompt": "How come every time I get instructions to meet someone they are never there?",
  "response": "There could be several reasons why you\u2019re finding that people aren\u2019t there when you follow instructions to meet them. Here are some possibilities to consider:\n\n1. **Miscommunication**:  \n   - The instructions might have been unclear or misunderstood. Double-check the details (time, location, etc.) with the person you\u2019re meeting to ensure you\u2019re on the same page.\n\n2. **Unreliable People**:  \n   - The person you\u2019re meeting might be unreliable, forgetful, or not prioritizing the meeting. If this happens often with the same person, it might be worth addressing the issue directly.\n\n3. **Wrong Location or Time**:  \n   - You might be going to the wrong place or showing up at the wrong time. Confirm the exact address, time zone, and any other specific details.\n\n4. **Technical Issues**:  \n   - If plans were made digitally (e.g., via text or email), there could have been a delay or error in sending/receiving the message.\n\n5. **Cultural or Social Norms**:  \n   - In some cultures or social circles, punctuality is less emphasized, and people might arrive late or not show up at all. Understanding the norms of the group you\u2019re dealing with can help manage expectations.\n\n6. **Lack of Confirmation**:  \n   - If the meeting wasn\u2019t firmly confirmed, the other person might have assumed it was tentative or canceled.\n\n7. **You\u2019re Arriving Late**:  \n   - If you\u2019re consistently late, the other person might have left by the time you arrive. Try to arrive at the agreed time or even a few minutes early.\n\n8. **Practical Barriers**:  \n   - The other person might have encountered unexpected issues (e.g., traffic, emergencies) that prevented them from showing up.\n\n**How to Avoid This in the Future**:  \n- Always confirm plans in advance and clarify all details.  \n- Use shared tools like calendars or apps to track meetings.  \n- Send a reminder message shortly before the meeting.  \n- If this happens repeatedly with the same person, discuss it with them to understand the problem.  \n\nIf this is a recurring issue with multiple people, it might be worth reflecting on whether there\u2019s a pattern in how plans are being communicated or followed up on.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
